To understand how thermodynamic constraints can guide the design of artificial systems for photochemical storage, it is best to start from minimal models that consider the thermodynamic constraints on the photovoltaic or photochemical solar energy conversion by exploring the analogy with efficient conversion in the solar or photovoltaic cell [3–5]. In productive photochemical conversion, the storage or downstream utilization is described as a single step conversion of solar energy into Gibbs free energy. Like the silicon solar cell, the photosynthetic solar cell is in its simplest form a molecular absorber that is excited and produces energy conversion by charge separation with rate I into an electron and hole in dynamic equilibrium with the absorber (Fig. 2). The excitation of a molecular Chl absorber in exchange with the field of solar irradiation leads to a difference in chemical potential1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
